{
  "texts": [
    "These tasks often have clearer evaluation criteria for success, potentially requiring less human guidance to define the problem and solution space.",
    "In software contexts, iterative innovation includes bug fixes, code cleanup, or code refactoring-activities that Hattori and Lanza (2008) categorize as maintenance-oriented.",
    "Our capability/iterative innovation framework distinctly emphasizes the cognitive processes and human input requirements in voluntary collaborative settings, unlike existing frameworks that focus on technological change or organizational outcomes (Table 1).",
    "The emergence of LLMs creates an interesting empirical question regarding their differential impact on these theoretically distinct innovation types.",
    "LLMs may disproportionately support iterative innovation because it requires less human input-developers can provide existing code and specify desired changes."
  ]
}